{
  "metadata": {
    "slug": "claude-liam-data",
    "title": "Claude, By the Numbers",
    "subtitle": "The Data Plugin",
    "channel": "claude-liam",
    "persona": "Kore",
    "folderLabel": "@HumanitariansAI",
    "audience": "Practitioners and makers following the channel's Claude workflows",
    "register": "Teardown",
    "engine": "kokoro",
    "voice": "af_kore",
    "palette": "claude",
    "typography": { "serif": "EB Garamond", "ui": "system sans", "mono": "SF Mono" },
    "model_chip": { "model": "Fable 5", "effort": "High" },
    "source": "books/anthropics/books/claude-cowork-plugins/chapters/ch07-data.txt",
    "derived_from": "claude-cowork-plugins.md (Ch.7)",
    "genre": "deep-explainer",
    "one_idea": "Without the data plugin your numbers sit in spreadsheets you never open; with it Claude does data exploration and the unglamorous-but-essential data cleaning, then answers real questions (which clients are declining?) — but the analysis is only as trustworthy as the data and the assumptions, so you still own the judgment.",
    "duration_estimate_s": 330,
    "lane_histogram_target": { "VOX": "20-25%", "MANIM": "25-40%", "REMOTION": "30-45%", "CARD": "remainder" }
  },
  "beats": [
    {
      "id": "B00", "act": "COLD OPEN", "lane": "ASK", "scene": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
      "greeting": "Olá, Kore",
      "props": { "command": "I have a year of revenue in a spreadsheet I never open. What's actually in it?", "runningText": "reading the file…", "output": ["Three clients carry most of it.", "One has been sliding since September."] },
      "narration_text": "Olá — this is Kore, in for Humanitarians AI. Somewhere on your drive is a spreadsheet you're a little afraid of. The data plugin opens it, cleans it, and answers the question you've been avoiding — in plain English. Here's how far that goes, and where you still hold the pen.",
      "show": "Claude composer on the cream stage: the avoided question typed in, the plain-English answer resolving below it.",
      "spark_line": "Open the spreadsheet."
    },

    { "id": "C01", "act": "ACT I", "lane": "CARD", "scene": "SegmentCard", "props": { "title": "The Unopened Spreadsheet" }, "narration_text": "Start with the file you never open.", "show": "Segment card: 'The Unopened Spreadsheet' in Title Case serif, warm ink on cream.", "spark_line": "The Unopened Spreadsheet" },
    {
      "id": "B01", "act": "ACT I", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "illustration/finances-folder-untouched",
      "narration_text": "Here's what solo operators won't admit: they're afraid of their own data. A folder called Finances, twelve months of revenue inside it, never opened — because opening it means analysis, and analysis means formulas, and formulas mean an hour of Googling VLOOKUP syntax and still not trusting the answer.",
      "show": "A folder icon labelled 'Finances' sits closed and dusty; a thought-bubble chain lights in turn — analysis, formulas, doubt.",
      "spark_line": "Afraid of the numbers."
    },
    {
      "id": "B02", "act": "ACT I", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/loop_export_stare_close.mp4",
      "narration_text": "So without the plugin, understanding your numbers looks like this loop. Export a CSV from your payment processor. Open it. Stare at rows and columns. Get a vague sense things are up or down. Close the file. Go back to work.",
      "show": "A four-step ring animates and closes on itself: export → stare → vague sense → close, then repeats.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "accumulate", "steps": ["export CSV", "stare at rows", "vague sense", "close the file"], "loop": true },
      "spark_line": "Export, stare, close."
    },
    {
      "id": "B03", "act": "ACT I", "lane": "VOX", "scene": "media/B03.png",
      "shot": { "type": "STILL", "source": "ai", "motion": "kenburns", "focus": [0.5, 0.45] },
      "narration_text": "And so the questions that actually matter go unanswered — not because they're unanswerable, but because answering them felt too hard. Decisions that should ride on data get made on gut feel instead.",
      "show": "A still of a person at a desk, spreadsheet glow on their face, hand closing a laptop; slow push-in.",
      "spark_line": "Too hard to face.",
      "pantry_note": "Tier 1 illustrative: solo operator at a dim desk closing a laptop mid-spreadsheet; documentary duotone, no readable numbers."
    },

    { "id": "C02", "act": "ACT II", "lane": "CARD", "scene": "SegmentCard", "props": { "title": "Ask It Plainly" }, "narration_text": "Now change how you ask.", "show": "Segment card: 'Ask It Plainly' in Title Case serif on cream.", "spark_line": "Ask It Plainly" },
    {
      "id": "B04", "act": "ACT II", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "SourceFlow",
      "narration_text": "With the plugin, you point Claude at that same file and ask the way you'd ask a colleague: which clients bring in the most revenue — and has the mix changed over the last two quarters?",
      "show": "A CSV flows in from the left; a plain-language question flows in beside it; a single sentence-answer resolves on the right.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "SourceFlow", "source": "your spreadsheet + a plain question", "target": "a plain-English answer" },
      "spark_line": "Point and ask."
    },
    {
      "id": "B05", "act": "ACT II", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "code-block",
      "narration_text": "No formula. No pivot table. Claude reads the data, runs the analysis, and hands back a sentence you can act on — in less time than it would take to write a SUM.",
      "show": "Onda code-block: a composer line typing the plain-language query, then the answer rendered as a sentence, not a grid.",
      "props": { "code": "> which clients generated the most revenue,\n  and has the mix shifted over the past two quarters?" },
      "spark_line": "No formula required."
    },
    {
      "id": "B06", "act": "ACT II", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/nlq_question_to_sentence.mp4",
      "narration_text": "That's natural-language querying. What were my total sales by month? Which client led last quarter? Am I spending more on software than I was six months ago? Claude translates each question into the right analysis, and returns a sentence — not a table of raw numbers.",
      "show": "A spoken question funnels through a translation node into an analysis, then narrows to a single highlighted sentence.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "divergence", "from": "a plain question", "to": "the right analysis → one sentence" },
      "spark_line": "Question in, answer out."
    },
    {
      "id": "B07", "act": "ACT II", "lane": "CARD", "scene": "SparkBeat",
      "narration_text": "It turns 'I think business is going okay' into something specific — say, three clients are sixty percent of revenue, and one's been sliding since September. That's the gap between reacting to problems and seeing them coming.",
      "show": "Spark beat: a vague phrase dissolves and a specific, dated finding sets in its place; terracotta underline on 'seeing them coming'.",
      "spark_line": "See it coming."
    },

    { "id": "C03", "act": "ACT III", "lane": "CARD", "scene": "SegmentCard", "props": { "title": "What It Actually Does" }, "narration_text": "Beyond answering, four kinds of work.", "show": "Segment card: 'What It Actually Does' in Title Case serif on cream.", "spark_line": "What It Actually Does" },
    {
      "id": "B08", "act": "ACT III", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "ChipGrid",
      "narration_text": "Exploration, cleaning, visualization, and comparison. Not every question needs all four — but together they're what turns a raw export into something you can trust and act on.",
      "show": "Four labelled chips resolve onto the stage: Explore · Clean · Visualize · Compare.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "ChipGrid", "chips": ["Explore", "Clean", "Visualize", "Compare"] },
      "spark_line": "Four kinds of work."
    },
    {
      "id": "B09", "act": "ACT III", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "SourceFlow",
      "narration_text": "Exploration first. Point Claude at a mystery export — a CSV of column headers that don't quite make sense — and it describes the structure, flags outliers, and, most valuably, suggests the questions worth asking. Often the best question isn't the one you started with.",
      "show": "Cryptic column headers flow in; a described structure, flagged outliers, and a list of suggested questions flow out.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "SourceFlow", "source": "a mystery CSV", "target": "structure + outliers + suggested questions" },
      "spark_line": "It suggests the question."
    },
    {
      "id": "B10", "act": "ACT III", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/clean_messy_to_tidy.mp4",
      "narration_text": "Cleaning. Messy data is the norm, not the exception — inconsistent date formats, duplicate rows, impossible values like negative sales. The plugin does this tedious work, and reports exactly what it changed.",
      "show": "A jumbled table settles into a tidy one as duplicates collapse and bad cells correct; a change-log accumulates alongside.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "threshold", "before": "messy rows: bad dates, duplicates, negatives", "after": "tidy table + a change-log" },
      "spark_line": "Fix the mess first."
    },
    {
      "id": "B11", "act": "ACT III", "lane": "VOX", "scene": "media/B11.png",
      "shot": { "type": "STILL", "source": "ai", "motion": "kenburns", "focus": [0.45, 0.5] },
      "narration_text": "Data cleaning is the unglamorous prerequisite to any useful analysis — and it's the biggest reason people never start. Automate it, and the barrier to actually working with your numbers just falls away.",
      "show": "A still of a cluttered desk of tangled receipts and printouts being squared into a neat stack; slow push-in.",
      "spark_line": "The unglamorous prerequisite.",
      "pantry_note": "Tier 1 illustrative: hands sorting a chaotic pile of paperwork into an ordered stack; documentary duotone, no readable text."
    },
    {
      "id": "B12", "act": "ACT III", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "illustration/column-becomes-chart",
      "narration_text": "Visualization. Show me monthly revenue for the past year, and you get a chart — for a deck, for a partner, or just to feel your own trajectory. Line charts for trends, bars for comparisons, and you can always ask for something different.",
      "show": "A single column of numbers lifts and morphs into a line chart, then swaps to a bar chart on cue.",
      "spark_line": "Numbers become a picture."
    },
    {
      "id": "B13", "act": "ACT III", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/compare_quarter_over_quarter.mp4",
      "narration_text": "And comparison. How does this quarter stack against last? Is my acquisition cost climbing or falling? This is where analysis earns its keep — and where most people quit, because building the comparison by hand is tedious. Totals tell you where you are; comparisons tell you where you're heading.",
      "show": "Two period bars sit side by side, then the delta between them animates into a rising or falling trend arrow.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "divergence", "from": "this period vs last period", "to": "the trajectory between them" },
      "spark_line": "Totals vs. trajectory."
    },

    { "id": "C04", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "CARD", "scene": "SegmentCard", "props": { "title": "The Monthly Habit" }, "narration_text": "Now make it a ritual.", "show": "Segment card: 'The Monthly Habit' in Title Case serif on cream.", "spark_line": "The Monthly Habit" },
    {
      "id": "B14", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "code-block",
      "narration_text": "Every business has a question it's been avoiding. Start there. Point Claude at your invoices and your expenses and just ask: am I profitable, month to month? It reads both files, correlates them, and gives you a real read on your financial health.",
      "show": "Onda code-block: the avoided question typed as a multi-line prompt against two named files, invoices and expenses.",
      "props": { "code": "> here are my invoices and my expenses for the year.\n  am I profitable month to month? which months were\n  strongest and weakest? any expense category growing\n  faster than revenue?" },
      "spark_line": "Ask the avoided question."
    },
    {
      "id": "B15", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "VOX", "scene": "media/B15.png",
      "shot": { "type": "STILL", "source": "ai", "motion": "kenburns", "focus": [0.4, 0.5], "vox_run": "R1",
        "handoff": { "camera": { "x": 0.4, "y": 0.5, "scale": 1.7 }, "objects": [ { "id": "operator", "x": 0.38, "y": 0.5, "scale": 1.0, "opacity": 1 } ] } },
      "narration_text": "You'll know more about your financial position after this five-minute conversation than you did after a year of 'I should really look at the numbers.'",
      "show": "A still of a person leaning into a laptop in the evening, focused, mid-conversation; slow push toward them.",
      "spark_line": "Five minutes, real clarity.",
      "pantry_note": "Tier 1 illustrative: solo operator absorbed at a laptop in warm evening light; documentary duotone. Continuity start of vox_run R1."
    },
    {
      "id": "B16", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "VOX", "scene": "media/B16.png",
      "shot": { "type": "STILL", "source": "ai", "motion": "kenburns", "focus": [0.6, 0.42], "vox_run": "R1",
        "handoff": { "camera": { "x": 0.6, "y": 0.42, "scale": 1.35 }, "objects": [ { "id": "operator", "x": 0.4, "y": 0.5, "scale": 0.9, "opacity": 1 }, { "id": "calendar", "x": 0.7, "y": 0.4, "scale": 1.0, "opacity": 1 } ] } },
      "narration_text": "So make it a ritual. First of the month, ten minutes: point Claude at last month's revenue and expenses and ask for a health check — total revenue, total expenses, margin, how it compares to the month before, and anything that looks off. It's the review a fractional CFO would give you, done in minutes.",
      "show": "The camera pulls back from B15's operator to reveal a wall calendar with the first of the month circled; same room grammar as B15.",
      "spark_line": "First of the month.",
      "pantry_note": "Tier 1 illustrative: same duotone treatment and room as B15, now wider to include a first-of-month calendar. Continuity end of vox_run R1."
    },
    {
      "id": "B17", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/accumulate_monthly_reviews.mp4",
      "narration_text": "Do it every month, and you're never surprised by your own numbers again. Each review stacks on the last until the trend is visible before it becomes a problem.",
      "show": "Monthly check-in markers drop onto a timeline one by one and connect into a clear, readable trend line.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "accumulate", "steps": ["month 1 check", "month 2 check", "month 3 check", "a visible trend"] },
      "spark_line": "Never surprised again."
    },
    {
      "id": "B18", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "code-block",
      "narration_text": "For service businesses, one question matters most: how concentrated is your revenue? Ask it directly — who are my top clients, what share rides on the top three, and is anyone quietly spending less than they used to?",
      "show": "Onda code-block: the client-concentration prompt typed line by line into the composer.",
      "props": { "code": "> analyze my client data. who are my top ten by revenue?\n  how concentrated is it — what share comes from my top\n  three? are any long-term clients spending less than\n  they used to?" },
      "spark_line": "Who carries the revenue?"
    },
    {
      "id": "B19", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/threshold_concentration_risk.mp4",
      "narration_text": "Concentration is one of the most important things a solo operator can know. If a single client is, say, forty percent of your income and you don't know it, you can't plan for the day they leave. The plugin makes that check trivial.",
      "show": "Revenue splits into client slices; one slice grows and crosses a marked risk threshold, flagged in terracotta.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "threshold", "before": "revenue split across clients", "after": "one slice crosses the concentration-risk line" },
      "spark_line": "One client, forty percent."
    },
    {
      "id": "B20", "act": "ACT IV", "lane": "VOX", "scene": "media/B20.png",
      "shot": { "type": "STILL", "source": "ai", "motion": "kenburns", "focus": [0.55, 0.5] },
      "narration_text": "And the follow-up is cheap. Of those top clients, which are declining? What changed last quarter that might explain it? Follow the thread — the plugin makes each next question almost free, so ask it.",
      "show": "A still of a finger tracing a downward line on a screen; slow drift along the line's descent.",
      "spark_line": "Follow the thread.",
      "pantry_note": "Tier 1 illustrative: a hand tracing a declining line on a monitor; documentary duotone, no readable figures."
    },

    { "id": "C05", "act": "ACT V", "lane": "CARD", "scene": "SegmentCard", "props": { "title": "You Own The Judgment" }, "narration_text": "Now the honest part.", "show": "Segment card: 'You Own The Judgment' in Title Case serif on cream.", "spark_line": "You Own The Judgment" },
    {
      "id": "B21", "act": "ACT V", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "PredictCard",
      "narration_text": "Here's the honest part. The plugin's analysis is only as trustworthy as two things: the data you fed it, and the assumptions underneath it. Clean inputs and sound assumptions give you a reliable read. Bad inputs give you confident, well-formatted nonsense.",
      "show": "A PredictCard weighs two inputs — data quality and assumptions — feeding a single trust output that swings with them.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "PredictCard", "claim": "trust = data quality x assumptions" },
      "spark_line": "Garbage in, garbage out."
    },
    {
      "id": "B22", "act": "ACT V", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/verify_before_rely.mp4",
      "narration_text": "That's exactly why it reports what it cleaned — so you can verify the fixes before you trust the numbers built on top of them. The change-log isn't paperwork. It's the audit trail.",
      "show": "The cleaning change-log presents line by line; each line gets a human check before the analysis above it unlocks.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "divergence", "from": "reported changes", "to": "verified → trusted analysis" },
      "spark_line": "Verify before you rely."
    },
    {
      "id": "B23", "act": "ACT V", "lane": "VOX", "scene": "media/B23.png",
      "shot": { "type": "STILL", "source": "ai", "motion": "drawon", "focus": [0.5, 0.45] },
      "narration_text": "The plugin can tell you a client is declining. It can't tell you whether to call them, discount, or let them go. It surfaces the number; you own the decision.",
      "show": "A still of a person paused over a chart at a decision point; a terracotta ring draws on around 'the decision' as the words land.",
      "spark_line": "You own the decision.",
      "pantry_note": "Tier 1 illustrative: a person pausing thoughtfully over a printed chart; ring annotation added at previz."
    },
    {
      "id": "B24", "act": "ACT V", "lane": "MANIM", "scene": "manim/accumulate_four_habits.mp4",
      "narration_text": "Four habits make it sing. Ask a specific question, not 'analyze my data.' Iterate — your first question breeds a better one. Compare, don't just total. And export on a schedule, because the plugin can only work with the data you actually give it.",
      "show": "Four habit tiles stack in order: Ask specific → Iterate → Compare → Export regularly.",
      "viz": { "pattern": "accumulate", "steps": ["Ask specific", "Iterate", "Compare, don't total", "Export regularly"] },
      "spark_line": "Specific, iterate, compare, export."
    },

    {
      "id": "V01", "act": "CLOSE", "lane": "REMOTION", "scene": "ClaudeVerdictArtifact",
      "lead_silence_s": 0.5,
      "narration_text": "Let's recap with Claude. The data plugin opens the spreadsheet you've been avoiding. It explores it, does the unglamorous cleaning, and answers real questions — which clients are declining, where you're actually profitable — in plain English. It's a monthly habit that keeps you from being surprised by your own numbers. And it's only as trustworthy as your data and your assumptions, so you keep the judgment.",
      "props": { "artifactLines": [ "Opens the file you never open", "Explores, cleans, and answers in plain English", "Comparisons, not just totals — see it coming", "A monthly habit: never surprised again", "Only as good as your data + assumptions — you own the call" ] },
      "show": "ClaudeVerdictArtifact: five verdict lines resolve in sequence on the cream stage after a half-second lead of silence.",
      "spark_line": "The verdict."
    },
    {
      "id": "H01", "act": "CLOSE", "lane": "ASK", "scene": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
      "greeting": "Your turn.",
      "props": { "command": "I have a spreadsheet of my invoices and a spreadsheet of my expenses for the past year. First, tell me what's in each file and flag anything that looks messy or wrong. Then give me a business-health check: am I profitable month to month, which months were strongest and weakest, and is any expense category growing faster than revenue? Then tell me the one follow-up question I should ask next.", "runningText": "paste this into Claude…" },
      "narration_text": "Your turn. Paste this into Claude: here's a spreadsheet of my invoices and one of my expenses for the year — tell me what's in each file and flag anything messy, then give me a business-health check: am I profitable month to month, which months were strongest and weakest, is any expense growing faster than revenue — and end with the one follow-up question I should ask next. It turns this chapter into a five-minute conversation about your actual money — run it, and notice the question it hands back. Kore, in for Humanitarians AI.",
      "show": "Claude composer: the full data-review prompt typed in, ready to send.",
      "spark_line": "Run your own numbers."
    },
    {
      "id": "O01", "act": "CLOSE", "lane": "CARD", "scene": "ClaudeTitleOutro",
      "narration_text": "Claude, By the Numbers.",
      "props": { "title": "Claude, By the Numbers", "handle": "@HumanitariansAI", "subline": "The Data Plugin" },
      "show": "Title outro card: 'Claude, By the Numbers' restated in serif over cream, handle and subline beneath.",
      "spark_line": "Claude, By the Numbers"
    }
  ]
}
